fields.title: Haiti sheltered campings [03.2010]
fields.abstract: This map layer shows the distribution of Modified Mercalli intensities (2% probability of exceedance in 500 years of return period) throughout Haiti, not including the effects of the ground. It was created by the NATHAT 1 Project, in May, 2010. The influence of Haiti’s most important identified tectonic fault is clear, particularly the Presqu’île du Sud Fault, where intensities might reach at least IX degrees. Most of the territory is exposed to intensities of at least VI degrees.

fields.title: Haiti Lithology Factor (Facteur De Lithologie) [05.2010]
fields.abstract: This map shows the result of the application of the Mora-Vahrson Methodology (http://www.google.com/search?hl=en&source=hp&q=mora-vahrson&aq=f&aqi=&aql=&oq=) for macro-zonation of susceptibility hazards to slope instability. It compiles the superposition of five parameters: relative relief, lithologic susceptibility, soil moisture, and intense earthquake and rainfall triggers. The scenario shows an important concentration of areas with middle and high susceptibility to slope instability in most of the southern Peninsula (massif de la Selle), the Septentrional (northern) Cordillera, Montagnes Noires and Montagnes du Trou d'Eau, north of the Cul-de-Sac depression.
